actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed SVG output and screenshots — that made the root cause clear.

The SVG canvas writes the closing `</svg>` tag when it is disposed (during its native destructor). In your code, `using var` defers disposal to the end of the enclosing scope, but `managedStream.ToArray()` is called before that point — so the closing tag hasn't been written yet.

Here's a workaround you can use right away — switch to a scoped `using` block for the canvas so it disposes before reading the stream:

```csharp
using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream);
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream))
{
    // ... draw on canvas ...
}
// Canvas is now disposed — closing </svg> tag has been written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

This matches the pattern used in our own test suite (`SvgCanvasSavesFile`). The reason `SKFileWStream` appeared to work is that you were reading the file after all disposals completed.

Regarding the 2.88.9 regression claim: the SVG canvas has always written the closing tag during disposal. It's possible you were using scoped `using` blocks in your older code, which would have disposed the canvas before reading.
